Explanation:

According to document 60.txt, Cowrie shells had been used in Uganda during the Nineteenth Century, and the British set an official exchange rate of 1 Penny equal to 50 Cowrie Shells. However, later on, it is mentioned that the Imperial British East Africa Company minted coins denominated in Rupees, Annas and Pice, following the British Indian monetary system. This suggests that the Rupee was indeed used as a currency in Uganda Protectorate, although not exclusively (Indian coins also circulated).
